node.text:
For me, there's a special joy in seeing animals living unnoticed in the background of human activity.

These guys are called mouthless land crabs. I don't know why they're called that, because it's untrue. They totally have mouths.

I actually used to have one of these as a pet. They're pretty commonly sold at reptile shows.

I always assumed that they were small animals. Usually when you see them they're the size of a quarter. 
They actually get to be quite large. Which I never realized before actually seeing them in the wild.

node.text:
I didn't know that snakes can swallow their own heads.

According to owner Luke Roland Martin on Facebook, the snake was eating a rabbit when the teeth caught in the fur and the snake's head folded into its own throat and was swallowed.

The snake sorted itself out later (3rd Pic)

I've seen snakes swallow their own tails but I've never seen anything like this before. I actually didn't know this was possible.

I know a lot of reptile keepers and veterinarians follow me. Have you guys seen anything like this before? How often does this happen, and do their teeth damage their own esophagous?

Does the snake usually sort itself out or does it usually take surgery to fix?

This is too cool to not share. The @blackwaterphotogroup is a bunch of sciba divers going out at night, and they're finding all these bizarre fish that no one has ever seen before.

I'm featuring some of ones that are identified. But there's plenty of animals that they're photographing, where we haven't been able to match up the adult form yet because they're so different looking. 

They're finding new and weird stuff everyday...check them out!

I took these pics in 2017, and to this day kills me that I didn’t get better photos of this. Posed better, lighted better, the bones on a white background presented meaningfully, with better detail of the evidence of months of repeated rib and spine breaks. I never sent in any samples for futher analysis. I didn’t give this animal the care, effort and respect he deserved.

Looking at this case now, it's possible that he had other bone disorders such as Osteomyelitis. 

Have you guys seen this before? Spinal problems are common in snakes, but the large swaths of bone over the ribs is not something Ive seen very often.

node.text:
This has been known and considered pretty cool since ancient times. Alexander the Great's horse supposedly had extra hooves.

Given that, I'm actually really surprised that this hasn't been bred out as a feature.

There are specific breeds of dogs and cats that are intentionally bred to have extra toes. Why not horses?

There were ancient cultures that practice horse fighting. It's like dog fighting but with horses. You would think that they would intentionally breed stallions with claws. But apparently not.

I get that it would take more maintenance, but that's never really stopped people before.

#teratology #teratologytuesday #teratologie

node.text:
You guys may have seen this already but it's super neat. 

This buck was found wandering around disoriented in a Tennessee neighborhood and was reported to authorities.

He has an incredibly rare eye condition in BOTH EYES.

It looks weird, but the thing over the eye is a perfectly normal patch of fur like the rest of his body. Its called a corneal dermoid cyst.

Sometimes during development when the embryo is forming, little bits of skin cells gets seperated from their kind and end up where they shouldn't be, take root, and make themselves at home in this new location. Ending up with situations like this.

Dermoid cyst occur in a lot of different animals (including people), and the skin that ends up on the eye is often perfectly normal. It has fur just like the rest of the body. It often has sweat glands, and even sheds.

The normal surface of the eye never formed, and instead is taken up by the wayward skin.

What surprises me the most about this case is how old the buck is. I'm shocked that he made it this long without being able to see.

Here's the kicker. He was euthanized by the authorities and tested for disease, and it turns out that he was not wandering around disoriented in a neighborhood because he was blind, he tested positive for EHD, which is a disease in deer that causes high fevers and confusion. So before getting EHD presumably he was just doing just fine. 

From the National Deer Association

I’m going through all these old posts for the book, so you guys are gonna see some of my earliest posts. I won't have a lot of time to make new stuff until it's done. 

One of the more common questions I get is: 

Where do you get your animals?

People usually think of things like hunting, or roadkill, but I think the answer is often a lot more mundane than expected.

Like.... well...Borrowing.

This young female river otter lived at a nature center until she died for some reason. 

After a veterinarian examined and necropsied her, she was stitched back up and left in the center's freezer for many years.

The nature center then wanted to do something with her, but because of serious freezer burn, her skin was no good for taxidermy anymore, so they sent her to the taxidermist to have her skeleton done. 

I borrowed her from the taxidermist for my class. We took a look at her, dissected her and returned the bones to the taxidermist.

No one seemed to want her skin, so I ended up with it. 

I still have it. She's decent, with some freezer damage. I used to bring her to my ecology classes, but I’ve not taught ecology in years, so she’s just in storage now. 

I'll probably sell her at some point. I dont know when she'd see classroom time again, especially since things are moving to mostly remote teaching now.

Here's a photo of me sketching her before the students arrive.
